@node "Other" "For those who live outside Russia"
@{lindent 1}
From the beginning this program was conceived for use in Russia, since I didn't imagine that anywhere else there's be such a hassle with coding... :(
The main recoding tables used in Russia are built into the program, but I see no obstacles to using my program in conformity with any other coding. Naturally, it should noted that during operation with external tables the option "Add Suffix" is turned off, since it is intended for operation with internal tables. As for all the rest, the operation of the program is in no way different.

@endnode
@node "Introduction" "About the program..."
@{jleft}@{lindent 1}
The program is designed to convert bitmapped (ordinary) fonts from one coding to another.

Some words about its capabilities:

 - Suitable for a font-sensitive GUI interface.
 - AppIcon support.
 - ToolTypes/CLI parameters to launch the program.
 - @{lindent 4}Built-in operation with the following codings:
   DM, DM2, 866 (MSDOS), KOI8, 1251 (WIN).@{lindent 1}
 - @{lindent 4}Capability for using external @{" recoding tables "  LINK  "FileFormat"}, comprising an ordinary text file, compatible with YAM charset files.@{lindent 1}
 - Optional export of the font in the asm source format.
 - Color font support.
 - Localization.

System requirements:

 - OS 3.0+
 - 020+ CPU

The first working version was written for OS 2.04 and MC68000, but later some OS 3.0 functions were activated. For this reason I stopped work on the MC68000 version, which made life easier for me...

@endnode
@node "Usage" "Use"
@{lindent 1}
Working with the program is very easy and does not require long and intensive study. Simply select a font and his coding (Input), then the coding in which you'd like to see it (Output) and press the button "Save As". If you want to use an external table for recoding then all you need to do is put a check mark opposite the corresponding gadget "Use Table" and select the required recoding table.

I'll write only a few words about the GUI since it's all understandable there:
@{lindent 2}
@{lindent 11}Input  - Coding of the input font@{lindent 2}
@{lindent 11}Output - Coding of the output font@{lindent 2}
@{lindent 11}Format - Switching the format for writing the font@{lindent 2}
@{lindent 11}YSize  - Font height@{lindent 2}
@{lindent 11}BLine  - Font baseline@{lindent 2}
@{lindent 11}LoChar - Lowest character code@{lindent 2}
@{lindent 11}HiChar - Highest character code@{lindent 2}
@{lindent 11}Bytes  - Font length in bytes (as opposed to the real length of the file, inasmuch only the size of the bitmap and tables (CharLoc, CharSpace, CharKern) are calculated here and all the rest, including the hunk header, reloc32, etc. are not considered)@{lindent 1}

Tooltypes/CLI parameters, default values in parentheses, abbreviations are given in conformance with launch from CLI:

@{lindent 18}SOURCEDIR=S/K  - Origin of the fonts being recoded (sys:fonts)@{lindent 1}
@{lindent 18}DESTDIR=D/K    - Place for writing recoded fonts (ram:)@{lindent 1}
@{lindent 18}TABLE=T/K      - Path to the recoding table@{lindent 1}
@{lindent 18}FONTNAME=FN/K  - Font name for the TransFont window. If nothing is entered or such a font is not found, the system font is used.@{lindent 1}
@{lindent 18}FONTSIZE=FS/N  - Font size indicated in the parameter FONTNAME; if there is no such size, the system font is used.@{lindent 1}
@{lindent 18}VIEWSTRING=V/K - Gadget View contents; that is, what will be shown in ClipRegion. It means this can be changed later "on the fly". If nothing is shown, then this line will contain some numbers and all the letters of the English alphabet.@{lindent 1}

"Add Suffix" - adds the font's coding to its name, for example:

@{jcenter}Topaz.font -> Topaz_alt.font, Topaz_win.font, Topaz_dm.font

@{jleft}It means if the recoding occurs according to an external table, then this is not possible. If when adding a suffix the size of the font name exceeds 32 symbols, then when the font is writing the suffix WILL NOT be added! This does not affect the situation where a font is writing as a source file. In such a case the name can exceed 32 symbols.

@{lindent 15}"All Sizes" - Turns on/off the recoding of all font sizes for one pass.@{lindent 1}
@{lindent 15}"Use Table" - Turns on/off the use of an external coding table.@{lindent 1}
@{lindent 15}"Font ID"   - Turns on/off the capability of using @{" Font ID " LINK "Font_ID"} of the font being converted.@{lindent 1}

@endnode
@node "FileFormat" "Recoding table format"
@{lindent 1}
Recoding table format:

====== Cut ======

 New Code   Old Code

   $41    =   $A7
   $61    =   $A8

====== Cut ======

How the recoding takes place. In the above table fragment instead of the symbol with code $A7 a symbol with code $41 will be entered etc.

The letter register and number of blanks plays no role; the main condition is: the dollar sign "$" goes first, then the hexadecimal number, then the equal sign "=", then the dollar sign again and the second number. All remaining lines are ignored.

N.B.! The hexadecimal number MUST be two numbers, for example:   $05,  $09,  etc, and not  $5,  $9.  Otherwise this line will be ignored in translating the table from text to binary format.

In iconifying the program the recoding table can be thrown on the TransFont icon - the table will be loaded and checked for correctness.

If you want to compile your own table then it would be useful to know the following:
To change the places of only a few symbols, you needn't write out the whole table since TransFont before checking a new table for correctness, fills its buffer 1:1, that is:

 $01 = $01
 $02 = $02
 $03 = $03
 etc...

And if only one symbol is chosen for recoding, then only it will be recoded!

@endnode
@node "Font_ID" "Identification String"
@{lindent 1}
Font ID - a small line, containing 31 ASCII symbols plus byte 0 and located inside the bitmap of the given font.

By standards it should contain there the name of the font and its size, but when opening the font this parameter is completely ignored by the system.
Accordingly, this field can be used for its own purposes. So several programs which work with fonts work this way, in particular the widely-known FED.

So that the information line is given by the Version command the following needs to be set up: "$VER: Name Version (Date) Comments". For example, you've converted some kind of font and want to preserve information about the creation date and the font's coding. So you need to change the "Font ID" in the following manner:

@{jcenter}$VER: topaz_win v1.0 (20.11.98)
@{jleft}@{lindent 1}
Why the "Font ID" needs to be turned on or off:
If you're converting only one font size, then this doesn't matter.
However, when converting fonts of various sizes (All Sizes ON), if you leave this option turned on, then the string content will be automatically copied into each file containing the bitmap size...
On the other hand - if you don't need this, then this is easy to turn off and not fill your head with nonsense. ;)  In this case the string will contain only one font name.

@endnode
